land and grassland to its current arid incarnation, Martin Williams takes us on a vivid journey through time. He describes how the desert’s ancient rocks were first fashioned, how dinosaurs roamed freely across the land, and how later, it was covered in tall trees. Williams discusses a plethora of questions: Why was the Sahara previously much wetter, and will it be so again? Did humans contribute to its desertification? What was the impact of extreme climatic episodes—such as prolonged droughts—upon the Sahara’s geology, ecology, and inhabitants? Williams shows how plants, animals, and humans have adapted to the Sahara and what lessons we might learn for living in harmony with the harshest, driest conditions in an ever-changing global environment.A valuable look at how an iconic region has changed over thousands of years, When the Sahara Was Green reveals the desert’s surprising past to reflect on its present, as well as its possible future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aClimatic changeszSahara. 0aDesertificationzAfrica, North. 0aPaleoclimatologyzSahara. 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh  aAeolian processes.  aAlgae.  aAlgeria.  aAlluvium.  aAmericas.  aAndes.  aAnthozoa.  aArid.  aAtlantic Ocean.  aBlack coral.  aBolivia.  aCarbon dioxide.  aChad Basin.  aChile.  aClimate change.  aCnidaria.  aCnidocyte.  aCoal.  aCoral reef.  aDate palm.  aDendrochronology.  aDeriba Caldera.  aDesert climate.  aDesert.  aDesertification.  aDrought.  aDry lake.  aDry valley.  aDune.  aEarth materials.  aEarth science.  aEarth's orbit.  aEast Africa.  aEcosystem.  aEcuadorians.  aEl Niño–Southern Oscillation.  aEmblem book.  aErosion.  aExploration.  aFar North (South Australia).  aFeather.  aFertilizer.  aFire coral.  